message.content:
 To save text to a local file in a JavaScript web app, you can use the FileSystem API. However, this API is not supported by all browsers and may require additional polyfills or libraries for compatibility. Here's an example of how to do it using the FileSystem API:

1. Check if the browser supports the FileSystem API:
```javascript
if (window.File && window.Blob && window.URL) {
  // The user agent supports the required APIs.
} else {
  alert("The user agent does not support the required APIS.");
}
```
2. Request permission to access the file system:
```javascript
window.requestFileSystem(PERSISTENT, 1024 * 1024, function (fileSystem) {
  // Successfully got a file system object.
}, errorHandler);
```
3. Create a new File and Blob objects:
```javascript
var text = "Hello World!";
var blob = new Blob([text], { type: 'text/plain' });
var file = new File([blob], 'helloWorld.txt', { type: 'text/plain' });
```
4. Write the content to a local file using the write function of the File object:
```javascript
file.write(function (progress) {
  // This event is fired each time some data has been written.
}, function () {
  console.log("Writing completed.");
});
```
5. Save the file to the local storage using the save method of the File object:
```javascript
file.save('helloWorld.txt');
```
Please note that this example is simplified and does not include error handling or other necessary steps for a production-ready application. You should also consider using libraries like [FileSaver.js](https://github.com/eligrey/FileSaver.js/) to ensure compatibility across different browsers.
